title: Redis 3.2.8 segfault
body:
Segfault on a pretty busy redis server running on AWS.  This is an r3.xlarge instance in the master role of a master/slave pair (as managed by separate sentinel processes running on both redis nodes and a 3rd arbiter node).  This is running on the default AWS ubuntu server image for us-east-1.

Full crash report from the logs follows.  Let me know if I can provide any other info.

comments_data.body:
I can reproducibly cause a segfault in redis 3.2.1 and 3.2.8 by running an `LRANGE` command on a specific key in my data set.

I've saved the data set, though it's kind of big.  Let me know if I can provide any other info.

It looks like we might have a case of #3527 - these were all lists created with redis 3.2.1.

I can actually reproduce the crash by doing an `lrange` on an number of list keys.  Is there any known fix for this?  I've tried running the same data in redis 3.2.8 but as mentioned above, it still crashes there.

The segfaults continue with redis 3.2.8, using keys that were written and subsequently read by redis 3.2.8.  So it's not #3527, or #3527 was not fixed in 3.2.1.  Redis is basically unusable for me at this point, it regularly crashes.

We use the index to store time series data where index[0] is the start date, and index[-1] is yesterday.  The data is put in as json, and if we want to know the last 60 days we would "lrange n-60 n".

The job that runs needs index[n-1] to exist in order to keep the date correct.  If it is missing it will insert an empty string to catch up to the index it's trying to insert on.
